Lecture 4: Subspace and Linear Independence â€‹

Topics: Â§2.1 â€” Subspaces, Column Space, Linear Independence, Basis, Dimension, Well-Definedness of Rank Date: Mar 13â€“19, 2026

ðŸŽ¯ Motivation: Is Rank Well-Defined? â€‹

In Lecture 3, we defined the rank of a matrix as:

Definition

Rank (Lecture 3 definition)

rank(A)=number of rank-one pieces from cross-filling

This definition has a subtle problem we mentioned but didn't resolve:

WARNING

The Well-Definedness Question

Cross-filling allows different pivot choices at each step. For example:

A=(246123369)
  • Choice 1: Pick pivot at position (1,1)
  • Choice 2: Pick pivot at position (2,2)
  • Choice 3: Pick pivot at position (3,3)

Do all choices give the same number of rank-one pieces?

What we know: Experiments suggest yes. What we need: A proof that rank doesn't depend on pivot choices.

Today's goal: Prove that rank is well-defined by discovering a deeper truth:

::: success The Key Insight (Preview)

Rank is not just "number of pieces from an algorithm" â€” it's a geometric property of the matrix:

rank(A)=dimension of the column space

The column space is a subspace (a geometric object), and its dimension (number of basis vectors) doesn't depend on how we compute it.

Strategy:

  1. Introduce subspaces, column space, linear independence, basis, dimension
  2. Show that cross-filling produces a basis for the column space
  3. Prove all bases have the same size (so dimension is well-defined)
  4. Conclude: rank = dimension (so rank is well-defined) âœ“ :::

This lecture elevates our perspective from algorithms to geometry.

1. Two Languages for Describing Subspaces â€‹

Before defining "subspace" formally, we need to understand two fundamentally different ways to describe sets.

1.1 The Daily Life Analogy â€‹

Suppose you want to tell someone where your classroom is:

Method A (Descriptive): "Find the room that satisfies these properties:

  • Has exactly 30 desks
  • Has windows facing south
  • Is on the 2nd floor"

Method B (Constructive): "Go to the 2nd floor, walk to the end of the hall, turn left, it's the last door."

Remark

Key Difference

Descriptive (Equation-Based)Constructive (Parametric)
How it worksList properties members must satisfyProvide a recipe to generate members
StrengthEasy to verify membershipEasy to generate new members
WeaknessHard to produce membersHard to verify membership
Example"Everyone wearing a red hat""Go 2nd floor, last door left"

Neither is better â€” they're complementary! We need both.

1.2 Two Languages in Linear Algebra â€‹

This duality appears throughout linear algebra:

Example

Example 1.1: Describing a line through the origin in R2

Consider the line y=2x through the origin:

Descriptive language (equation):

L={(xy):y=2x}
  • To verify (36)âˆˆL: Check 6=2(3) âœ“
  • To generate members: Hard! Need to solve for x given constraint

Constructive language (parametric):

L={t(12):tâˆˆR}
  • To generate members: Pick any t! E.g., t=3 gives (36)
  • To verify (36)âˆˆL: Hard! Need to find t such that t(12)=(36)

Both describe the same line, but with opposite strengths!

Example

Example 1.2: A plane through the origin in R3

Descriptive: P={(xyz):x+y+z=0}

Constructive: P={s(10âˆ’1)+t(01âˆ’1):s,tâˆˆR}

Again, same plane, two languages!

Why does this matter for matrices?

::: success The Connection to Matrices

For a matrix A:

  • Null space = {x : Ax=0} â€” descriptive (equation-based)
  • Column space = {Ax : xâˆˆRn} â€” constructive (parametric)

Understanding both languages helps us solve Ax=b:

  • Question: Is b in the column space? (verification â€” hard in constructive language)
  • Answer: Solve Ax=b (finding parameters â€” hard in descriptive language)

They're dual views of the same problem! :::

2. Subspaces: Flat Spaces Through the Origin â€‹

2.1 Definition â€‹

Definition

Subspace

A subspace W of Rn (or more generally, a vector space V) is a non-empty subset that is closed under linear combinations:

For any u,vâˆˆW and any scalars Î±,Î²âˆˆR:

Î±u+Î²vâˆˆW

Equivalently (check these conditions):

  1. 0âˆˆW (contains the zero vector)
  2. If u,vâˆˆW, then u+vâˆˆW (closed under addition)
  3. If uâˆˆW and Î±âˆˆR, then Î±uâˆˆW (closed under scaling)

TIP

Geometric Intuition

A subspace is a flat space that:

  • Passes through the origin (must contain 0)
  • Is closed under vector operations (if you add/scale vectors in the space, you stay in the space)

Visual: Lines through origin, planes through origin, Rn itself, or just {0}.

Non-examples:

  • Line y=2x+1 (doesn't pass through origin)
  • Unit circle (not closed under scaling)

4. Linear Independence and Basis â€‹

To understand when column space is "efficiently" described, we need linear independence.

4.1 Linear Independence â€‹

Definition

Linearly Independent

A list of vectors v1,v2,â€¦,vk is linearly independent if:

c1v1+c2v2+â‹¯+ckvk=0âŸ¹c1=c2=â‹¯=ck=0

4.2 Left Cancellation Property (Equivalent Characterization) â€‹

Linear independence has a powerful matrix interpretation:

Proposition

Linear Independence âŸº Left Cancellation

Let U=(u1u2â‹¯ur) (columns u1,â€¦,ur).

The following are equivalent:

  1. Columns of U are linearly independent
  2. Left cancellation holds: UP=UQâŸ¹P=Q
  3. Null space is trivial: Ux=0âŸ¹x=0

Why equivalent?

(1) âŸº (3): By definition! Linear independence says âˆ‘ciui=0â‡’ all ci=0, which is exactly Uc=0â‡’c=0.

(3) âŸ¹ (2): If UP=UQ, then U(Pâˆ’Q)=0. By (3), each column of Pâˆ’Q must be zero, so P=Q.

(2) âŸ¹ (3): Special case where Q=O (zero matrix).

TIP

Why "Left" Cancellation?

The matrix U appears on the left in UP=UQ, and we can "cancel" it to get P=Q.

Contrast: If columns are dependent, we cannot cancel!

Example: (1212)(10)=(1212)(00.5)=(11)

But (10)â‰ (00.5)! Cancellation fails because columns are dependent.

4.3 Span â€‹

Definition

The span of vectors v1,â€¦,vk is the set of all their linear combinations:

span{v1,â€¦,vk}={c1v1+â‹¯+ckvk:c1,â€¦,ckâˆˆR}

Terminology: We say {v1,â€¦,vk} spans W if span{v1,â€¦,vk}=W.

Remark

Connection to Column Space

Col(A)=span{columns ofÂ A}

They're the same thing! Column space is the span of columns.

4.4 Basis â€‹

Definition

Basis

A basis for a subspace W is a list of vectors {e1,â€¦,er} that:

  1. Spans W: Every vector in W can be written as a linear combination of e1,â€¦,er
  2. Is linearly independent: No redundancy

Equivalently: A basis is a minimal spanning set or a maximal independent set.

TIP

Basis = Efficient Coordinates

A basis gives a unique coordinate system for W:

If {e1,â€¦,er} is a basis, then every vâˆˆW can be written uniquely as:

v=c1e1+â‹¯+crer

Why unique?

  • Spanning ensures existence (you can write v this way)
  • Independence ensures uniqueness (only one way to do it)

Proof of uniqueness: Suppose v=c1e1+â‹¯+crer=d1e1+â‹¯+drer. Then:

(c1âˆ’d1)e1+â‹¯+(crâˆ’dr)er=0

By independence, all ciâˆ’di=0, so ci=di for all i. âœ“

  • Spans R3: Any (xyz)=xe1+ye2+ze3 âœ“

5. Cross-Filling Produces a Basis for Col(A) â€‹

Now we return to cross-filling with new tools. Recall from Lecture 3:

A=UV=âˆ‘i=1ruiviT

where U=(u1â‹¯ur) collects the column vectors from each rank-one piece.

Key question: What is special about U's columns?

5.1 Property 1: U's Columns Are Linearly Independent â€‹

Proposition

Columns of U (from cross-filling) are linearly independent

Let A=UV be the factorization from cross-filling, where U=(u1â‹¯ur).

Then {u1,â€¦,ur} are linearly independent.

Proof idea: Use the pivot structure from cross-filling. Each ui came from a rank-one piece with a specific pivot position, and these pivots form a "staircase" pattern that forces independence.

Example

Example 5.1: Why cross-filling gives independent columns

Recall Example 2.3 from Lecture 3:

A=(246124369)=(201130)(123001)U=(201130),u1=(213),u2=(010)

Check independence: c1u1+c2u2=0

c1(213)+c2(010)=(2c1c1+c23c1)=(000)

Solve backwards (this is the key technique!):

  • From row 2: The pivot for u2 was in position (2,3) (column 3 of A, which became column 2 of U)
  • In the remainder after peeling u1, row 1 was zero, so u2 has a unique nonzero entry in row 2
  • From equation: c1+c2=0 and u1 had row 1 already nonzero
  • Looking at row 2: c1+c2=0, but wait, let me recalculate...

Actually, let me use the pivot row method more carefully:

Observation:

  • u1 came from pivot at position (1,1) â€” row 1 was the pivot row
  • u2 came from pivot at position (2,3) â€” row 2 was the pivot row (in the remainder)

Key property: After peeling u1, row 1 of the remainder was zero. So u2 doesn't "care" about row 1.

Looking at the structure:

u2=(010)â†First entry is 0 (row 1 was eliminated)

Backward substitution:

  • Row 3: 3c1=0â‡’c1=0
  • Row 1: 2c1=0 âœ“ (consistent)
  • Row 2: c1+c2=0+c2=0â‡’c2=0

All coefficients zero! So independent âœ“

Why did this work? The pivot structure creates a triangular pattern â€” later pivots don't interfere with earlier pivot rows, allowing backward substitution to uniquely determine all coefficients must be zero.

::: proof Proof (General Case): Pivot Row Method

Let u1,â€¦,ur be the columns from cross-filling, where ui came from the rank-one piece with pivot in row pi.

Key observation: After peeling R1,â€¦,Riâˆ’1, rows p1,â€¦,piâˆ’1 of the remainder are zero. Therefore:

ui[rowÂ pj]=0for allÂ j<i

(The i-th column has zeros in all previous pivot rows)

Check independence: Suppose c1u1+â‹¯+crur=0.

Solve backwards:

  1. Look at pivot row pr (last pivot):

    • All u1,â€¦,urâˆ’1 have zero in row pr (by observation above)
    • So: crâ‹…(ur[rowÂ pr])=0
    • Since pivot entry is nonzero: ur[rowÂ pr]â‰ 0
    • Therefore: cr=0 âœ“

  2. Look at pivot row prâˆ’1 (second-to-last):

    • All u1,â€¦,urâˆ’2 have zero in row prâˆ’1
    • We know cr=0
    • So: crâˆ’1â‹…(urâˆ’1[rowÂ prâˆ’1])=0
    • Since pivot entry nonzero: crâˆ’1=0 âœ“

  3. Continue backwards: crâˆ’2=0,â€¦,c1=0

All coefficients zero, so the columns are linearly independent! âœ“ :::

5.2 Property 2: Col(U)=Col(A) (The "Mother Body" Argument) â€‹

Proposition

Column spaces are equal

If A=UV is from cross-filling, then:

Col(U)=Col(A)

Proof (Two inclusions):

Part 1: Col(A)âŠ†Col(U)

Since A=UV, any vector in Col(A) has the form:

Ax=UVx=U(Vx)

Let y=Vx. Then Ax=UyâˆˆCol(U) âœ“

Part 2: Col(U)âŠ†Col(A) â€” The Mother Body Argument ðŸ”¬

This is the deeper direction! We need to show every column of U is a linear combination of columns of A.

Key idea: Cross-filling peels columns from the mother matrix A. Each ui is obtained by taking a column of a remainder matrix, and remainders are built from A.

Detailed argument:

Recall cross-filling process:

  • Start with A1=A
  • Peel off R1=u1v1T, where u1 is a column of A1 (possibly scaled)
  • Remainder: A2=A1âˆ’R1
  • Peel off R2=u2v2T, where u2 is a column of A2 (possibly scaled)
  • And so on...

Claim: Every column of Ak is a linear combination of columns of A.

Proof by induction:

  • Base: A1=A âœ“

  • Step: Ak+1=Akâˆ’Rk=Akâˆ’ukvkT

    Each column of Ak+1 has the form:

    (Ak)jâˆ’(ukvkT)j=(Ak)jâˆ’vkjuk

    This is a linear combination of:

    • Column j of Ak (by induction hypothesis, is a combination of A's columns)
    • uk (which is a column of Ak, so also a combination of A's columns)

    Both are combinations of A's columns, so their combination is too! âœ“

Conclusion: Since ui is a column of some Ak, it's a linear combination of A's columns.

Therefore uiâˆˆCol(A) for all i, which means Col(U)âŠ†Col(A) âœ“

Combining both parts: Col(U)=Col(A) âœ“

TIP

The "Mother Body" Metaphor ðŸ§¬

Think of A as the mother body (æ¯ä½“) that contains all the genetic material.

Cross-filling peels off layers (R1,R2,â€¦), but each peeled piece is made from:

  • Columns of the current remainder (which inherit from A)
  • Scaled and combined from A's columns

No new material is introduced â€” everything comes from the mother body A!

This is why Col(U)âŠ†Col(A): the columns we collect (u1,â€¦,ur) are all descendants of A's columns.

6. Well-Definedness: Dimension and Rank â€‹

Now we prove the main theorems that make dimension and rank well-defined.

6.1 Dimension is Well-Defined â€‹

Theorem

All Bases Have the Same Size

Let W be a subspace. If {u1,â€¦,um} and {v1,â€¦,vn} are both bases for W, then:

m=n

Consequence: Dimension is well-defined â€” it doesn't matter which basis we use to count!

::: proof Proof (Change-of-Basis Matrices + Trace)

Let:

  • Basis 1: U=(u1â‹¯um) (columns)
  • Basis 2: V=(v1â‹¯vn) (columns)

Step 1: Since Basis 2 spans W, every vector in Basis 1 can be written as a combination of Basis 2:

U=VP

for some nÃ—m matrix P (change-of-basis matrix from U to V).

Step 2: Similarly, since Basis 1 spans W:

V=UQ

for some mÃ—n matrix Q (change-of-basis matrix from V to U).

Step 3: Substitute the second into the first:

U=VP=(UQ)P=U(QP)

Step 4: Since columns of U are linearly independent, we can apply left cancellation:

U=U(QP)âŸ¹QP=Im

(Here Im is the mÃ—m identity matrix)

Step 5: Similarly, substitute the first into the second:

V=UQ=(VP)Q=V(PQ)

Since columns of V are linearly independent:

V=V(PQ)âŸ¹PQ=In

Step 6: Now we have:

  • QP=Im (an mÃ—m matrix)
  • PQ=In (an nÃ—n matrix)

Take the trace of both:

tr(QP)=tr(Im)=mtr(PQ)=tr(In)=n

Step 7: Use the cyclic property of trace:

tr(QP)=tr(PQ)

(For any matrices A (size kÃ—â„“) and B (size â„“Ã—k), we have tr(AB)=tr(BA))

Step 8: Combine:

m=tr(QP)=tr(PQ)=n

Therefore: m=n âœ“

Conclusion: Any two bases for W have the same number of vectors! :::

Remark

Why the Trace Trick Works ðŸŽ©

The trace tr(M)=m11+m22+â‹¯+mkk (sum of diagonal) has a special property:

tr(AB)=tr(BA)

Example:

A=(1234),B=(5678)AB=(19224350),tr(AB)=19+50=69BA=(23343146),tr(BA)=23+46=69$$âœ“âˆ—âˆ—Whytrueingeneral?âˆ—âˆ—$$(AB)ii=âˆ‘jaijbji,(BA)jj=âˆ‘ibjiaij

Summing over i vs j gives the same double sum!

In our proof: Even though QP is mÃ—m and PQ is nÃ—n (different sizes!), their traces are equal, forcing m=n.

::: success Dimension is Now Well-Defined!

For any subspace W:

dimâ¡(W)=number of vectors in any basis forÂ W

This is independent of which basis we choose! ðŸŽ‰ :::

6.2 Rank is Well-Defined â€‹

Now we connect rank to dimension:

Theorem

Rank = Dimension of Column Space

For any matrix A:

rank(A)=dimâ¡(Col(A))

Proof:

From Â§5.3, we know:

  • Cross-filling produces A=UV where U has r columns
  • The columns of U form a basis for Col(A)
  • Therefore dimâ¡(Col(A))=r (number of basis vectors)

But by Lecture 3 definition:

  • rank(A)=r (number of rank-one pieces from cross-filling)

Therefore: rank(A)=dimâ¡(Col(A)) âœ“

::: success Rank is Well-Defined! ðŸŽŠ

Why? Because:

  1. rank(A)=dimâ¡(Col(A)) (just proved)
  2. dimâ¡(Col(A)) is well-defined (Â§6.1 â€” all bases have same size)
  3. Therefore rank(A) is well-defined (doesn't depend on pivot choices!) âœ“

Different cross-filling runs (with different pivot choices) may give:

  • Different U matrices
  • Different V matrices
  • Different rank-one pieces R1,R2,â€¦

But they all give:

  • Same number r of pieces (because r=dimâ¡(Col(A)), a geometric property)
  • Same column space Col(A) :::

Example

One rank-one piece â†’ rank(A)=1

Both give rank 1 because:

Col(A)={t(21):tâˆˆR}

is a 1-dimensional subspace (a line), regardless of how we compute it!

7. Summary and Perspective Elevation â€‹

What We Achieved Today ðŸŽ¯ â€‹

::: success From Algorithm to Geometry

Lecture 3: Rank was defined algorithmically (count rank-one pieces from cross-filling)

  • Problem: Different pivot choices might give different counts (not well-defined)

Lecture 4: Rank is redefined geometrically:

rank(A)=dimâ¡(Col(A))
  • Solution: Dimension is well-defined (all bases have same size)
  • Therefore rank is well-defined (independent of algorithm choices) âœ“

The key insight: Cross-filling doesn't just decompose A â€” it finds a basis for Col(A)! :::

Key Theorems Proved â€‹

Theorem

Summary of Main Results

  1. Cross-filling extracts a basis: If A=UV from cross-filling, then columns of U form a basis for Col(A)

  2. Dimension is well-defined: All bases for a subspace have the same number of vectors

  3. Rank is well-defined: rank(A)=dimâ¡(Col(A)), independent of cross-filling choices
